      <p>
        I studied at Vanderbilt, where I majored in American Studies with highest honors and minored in Economics. After college I worked on finEQUITY, a project focused on financial empowerment for formerly incarcerated people — which deepened a sustained interest in how policy, place, and people interact, and pointed me toward planning as the field where those threads converge.
      </p>
      <p>
        Across these projects — the People's Guide to Nashville from freshman year, the senior thesis on felonism, the 1940neighbors mapping work — the work returns to the same questions: who gets remembered and who gets erased in the places we live, and what tools can make those layers legible to more people.
      </p>
      <p>
        My research interests sit at the intersection of place, memory, displacement, and the built environment, using mixed methods and a commitment to data accessibility. I'm starting Georgia Tech's MCRP program in Fall 2026 and am actively looking for a Graduate Research Assistantship aligned with that work.
      </p>
      <p>
        I use Claude Code as a build partner for most of my technical work. It lets me ship more, faster, while keeping the design and research decisions firmly my own.
